# M7b integration: `rtc` object class.
# Both the legacy `set-time` command and the new `rtc.time` attribute
# read/write the same state — flipping one and reading via the other
# is the strongest test of view-vs-state separation. PRAM access goes
# through pram_read / pram_write methods (the legacy shell parser
# doesn't have `=` so attr assignment lands with the M9 cutover).

run 50000

# Read-only views.
eval rtc
rtc.read_only

# Set the time via the legacy command — expects unix epoch.
# 1969-12-31T23:59:59 UTC is unix epoch -1; pick a positive value.
# 0 unix → 1970-01-01T00:00:00 UTC → 2082844800 mac seconds.
rtc.time = 0
rtc.time

# Set a different time, observe again.
rtc.time = 1000000
rtc.time

# PRAM read of a known address. Mac PRAM is initialised by the boot
# code, so the contents depend on how far through boot we are. We
# write a sentinel and read it back via the same path.
echo $(rtc.pram_write(0x80, 0xAB))
echo $(rtc.pram_read(0x80))

# Read the full PRAM snapshot — output is "0x..." hex string.
rtc.pram

quit
